<dl id="n11142g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n11" href="#n11142g">N11 (VI.B.5)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n11all.htm#n11142g"> 142(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> France / 1) Frank (civic) / 2) Latin (intellect) / 3) Celt (soul // Ireland / <font color="green">[1]</font> English / <font color="green">[2]</font> Latin / <font color="green">[3]</font> Celt</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Celtes, Latin et Franks, trois races, trois g&eacute;nies, trois mondes, si oppos&eacute;s qu&apos;ils paraissent irr&eacute;conciliables. Et pourtant le g&eacute;nie fran&ccedil;ais n&apos;est-il pas justement le r&eacute;sultat de leur harmonie ou de leur &eacute;quilibre instable? A toutes le &eacute;poques de notre histoire, on les voit se battre, se m&ecirc;ler et s&apos;unir sans | jamais se confondre totalement. S&apos;il me fallait caract&eacute;riser d&apos;un aper&ccedil;u sommaire <i>la trinit&eacute; vivante</i> qui constitue cet &ecirc;tre moral qu&apos;on appelle <i>la nation fran&ccedil;aise</i>, je dirais que <mark><i>le g&eacute;nie frank</i>, par la monarchie et la f&eacute;odalit&eacute;</mark>, en constitua l&apos;ossature et <i>le corps solide</i>; <mark><i>le g&eacute;nie latin</i></mark>, qui nous a si fortement imprim&eacute; son sceau et sa forme par la conqu&ecirc;te romaine, par l&apos;&Eacute;glise et par l&apos;Universit&eacute;, y joue le r&ocirc;le de <mark><i>l&apos;intellect</i></mark>. Quant au <mark><i>g&eacute;nie celtique</i></mark>, c&apos;est &agrave; la fois le sang qui coule dans ses veines,<i> <mark>l&apos;&acirc;me</mark> profonde</i> qui agite son corps et sa conscience seconde, secr&egrave;te inspiratrice de son intellect. <br><font color="green">[Celts, Latin and Franks, three races, three genies, three worlds, so opposite that they seem irreconcilable. And yet is not French genius the result of their harmony or unstable equilibrium? At all times of our history, we see them fight, mingle and unite without ever getting totally confused. If I had to characterize the living trinity which constitutes this moral being, which is called the French nation, from a brief overview, I would say that the Frankish genius, through monarchy and feudalism, constituted its skeleton and solid body; the Latin genius, which has so strongly impressed upon us its seal and its form by the Roman conquest, by the Church and by the University, plays the part of the intellect. As for Celtic genius, it is at the same time the blood that flows in its veins, the deep soul which agitates its body and its second conscience, secret inspiring of its intellect.]</font> <small> &Eacute;douard Schur&eacute;, <a name="ESLG" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#ESLG"><cite title="source">Les Grandes L&eacute;gendes de France</cite></a> (1921, 1892) 193-4</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Joyce has arranged this account of the racial makeup of France and Ireland as a table with two columns. </mm> </dd></dl>
